dev/interface-inventory/option3-contract-first/findings.md:39:- `short explanation`: Observability/reporting contract breadth exceeds acceptance coverage in a few places. The docs claim a stable `fathomdb` payload key in host records and a recovery progress-stream schema owned by recovery, but acceptance only locks the lifecycle enum, selected diagnostic fields, `check-integrity`, and some CLI reachability.
dev/interface-inventory/option3-contract-first/findings.md:47:- `short explanation`: The architecture rows for `lifecycle`, `recovery`, and `bindings facade` flatten multiple contract classes too aggressively. `lifecycle` combines response-cycle events, diagnostics, counters, and profiling; `recovery` combines two CLI roots plus report schemas; `bindings facade` combines public verb parity, error mapping, cursor exposure, and deprecation policy.
dev/notes/context-research/set1/context-research-tech-docs.md:15:- [How to write a good spec for AI agents (Addy Osmani)](https://addyosmani.com/blog/good-spec/) — Practitioner guidance on spec scope, attention budget, and spec-quality / output-quality coupling.
dev/notes/context-research/set1/context-research-tech-docs.md:18:- [Repository map (Aider docs)](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html) — Aider's PageRank-style symbol map approach with a default 1k-token budget.
dev/notes/context-research/set1/context-research-tech-docs.md:35:**Observations:** The frontier consensus across Anthropic, Cursor, and the Claude Code community is to treat tech docs as a _file system_ the agent navigates, not as prompt payload. This converges with Aider's repo-map approach, which sends only "the most relevant portions of the repo map" using a graph-ranking algorithm and a 1k-token default budget — [Aider](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html).
dev/notes/context-research/set1/context-research-tech-docs.md:42:**Observations:** Spec-driven approaches help, but two failure modes recur: (a) implementation detail leaking into spec ("Focus on WHAT users need and WHY" while avoiding "HOW to implement" — spec-kit), and (b) over-stuffed specs that exceed the model's "attention budget." The Stage-1 registered report on spec-driven generation (arXiv 2601.03878) is _not yet_ empirical, so the strongest empirical signal in this area is currently from spec-quality interventions in adjacent domains (see F5 on OpenAPI).
